<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,330,1556]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,303,330,356]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Description.</emphasis>
Fastigium verticis narrow, compressed, conical, shorter than scapus; dorsal surface with or without a faint swelling at base; ventral margin separated by a shallow but distinct sinuosity from fastigium frontis. Frons matt or shining, with some shallowly impressed dots; genae subsmooth (
<figureCitation box="[1198,1293,410,436]" captionStart="FIGURES 80–85" captionStartId="24.[151,269,1891,1915]" captionTargetBox="[244,1344,181,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-83@24.[236,1350,176,1867]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 80–85. Pseudomacroxiphus szentia: 80, male holotype of P. atrifrons; 81, female paratype of P. atrifrons; 82, frons holotype of P. atrifrons; 83, stridulatory area of left tegmen male holotype of P. szentia; 84, do. of right tegmen male paratype of P. atrifrons; 85, ovipositor female paratype of P. atrifrons. Scales = 1 mm (82–84) or 10 mm (81, 85)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5123660" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5123660/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 82</figureCitation>
). Pronotum subsmooth, rather broad and low, disc broadly rounded into paranota, very apical area slightly raised, flat and shouldered; anterior margin broadly rounded but concave in middle; posterior margin truncate; transverse sulcus faint, broadly interrupted in middle; second transverse sulcus distinct on paranota, obsolete on disc (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 80–85" captionStartId="24.[151,269,1891,1915]" captionTargetBox="[244,1344,181,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-83@24.[236,1350,176,1867]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 80–85. Pseudomacroxiphus szentia: 80, male holotype of P. atrifrons; 81, female paratype of P. atrifrons; 82, frons holotype of P. atrifrons; 83, stridulatory area of left tegmen male holotype of P. szentia; 84, do. of right tegmen male paratype of P. atrifrons; 85, ovipositor female paratype of P. atrifrons. Scales = 1 mm (82–84) or 10 mm (81, 85)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5123660" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5123660/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 80</figureCitation>
). Paranota with ventral margin almost straight, descending posteriorly (
<figureCitation box="[1055,1146,570,596]" captionStart="FIGURES 80–85" captionStartId="24.[151,269,1891,1915]" captionTargetBox="[244,1344,181,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-83@24.[236,1350,176,1867]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 80–85. Pseudomacroxiphus szentia: 80, male holotype of P. atrifrons; 81, female paratype of P. atrifrons; 82, frons holotype of P. atrifrons; 83, stridulatory area of left tegmen male holotype of P. szentia; 84, do. of right tegmen male paratype of P. atrifrons; 85, ovipositor female paratype of P. atrifrons. Scales = 1 mm (82–84) or 10 mm (81, 85)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5123660" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5123660/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 81</figureCitation>
). Fully winged; tegmen with apex rounded; hind wings of same length as tegmina (
<figureCitation box="[886,978,610,636]" captionStart="FIGURES 80–85" captionStartId="24.[151,269,1891,1915]" captionTargetBox="[244,1344,181,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-83@24.[236,1350,176,1867]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 80–85. Pseudomacroxiphus szentia: 80, male holotype of P. atrifrons; 81, female paratype of P. atrifrons; 82, frons holotype of P. atrifrons; 83, stridulatory area of left tegmen male holotype of P. szentia; 84, do. of right tegmen male paratype of P. atrifrons; 85, ovipositor female paratype of P. atrifrons. Scales = 1 mm (82–84) or 10 mm (81, 85)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5123660" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5123660/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 81</figureCitation>
). Prosternal spines of medium length (shorter than coxa), but very stout. Mesosternal lobes angular or rounded, metasternal lobes rounded; medial plate at both posterior angles with an obtuse cone. Knee lobes of pro- and mesofemora spinose on both sides (spine on external side of profemur often short, mesofemur on external side sometimes bi-spinose); of postfemur bi-spinose on both sides.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,330,1556]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
Male. Stridulatory area of tegmen with mirror almost quadrangular and behind mirror with a series of additional fields without nervature, separated from each other by subparallel transverse veins (
<figureCitation box="[1277,1423,850,876]" captionStart="FIGURES 80–85" captionStartId="24.[151,269,1891,1915]" captionTargetBox="[244,1344,181,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-83@24.[236,1350,176,1867]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 80–85. Pseudomacroxiphus szentia: 80, male holotype of P. atrifrons; 81, female paratype of P. atrifrons; 82, frons holotype of P. atrifrons; 83, stridulatory area of left tegmen male holotype of P. szentia; 84, do. of right tegmen male paratype of P. atrifrons; 85, ovipositor female paratype of P. atrifrons. Scales = 1 mm (82–84) or 10 mm (81, 85)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5123660" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5123660/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Figs. 83–84</figureCitation>
). Tenth abdominal tergite transverse but slightly descending posteriorly; apical margin roundly excised in middle and with a rounded projecting lobe at both sides of excision (
<figureCitation box="[937,1084,930,956]" captionStart="FIGURES 86–94" captionStartId="25.[151,269,1853,1877]" captionTargetBox="[159,1428,182,1825]" captionTargetId="figure-109@25.[151,1436,170,1830]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURES 86–94. Pseudomacroxiphus szentia details: 86–87, Titillators in ventro-distal view; 88, do. in latero-distal view; 89, do. in dorso-proximal view; 90–91, male abdominal apex in dorsal view; 92 female subgenital plate in ventral view; 93 do. in lateral view; 94, male stridulatory file on underside of left tegmen.—86–87, 91, 94, holotype male of P. szentia; 88–89, holotype male of P. atrifrons; 90, paratype male of P. atrifrons; 92–93, paratype female of P. atrifrons. Abbreviations: 10t tenth abdominal tergite; ce cercus; e epiproct; s stylus; sg subgenital plate. Scales = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5123664" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5123664/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Figs. 90–91</figureCitation>
). Epiproct rounded triangular with a faint medial sulcus in basal half. Projections of paraprocts rather long, stout, conical and curved mediad. Subgenital plate with apex roundly excised in middle, on both sides of excision with short and stout projections which carry the styli; styli as long as or little longer than excised area (
<figureCitation box="[1117,1204,1050,1076]" captionStart="FIGURES 86–94" captionStartId="25.[151,269,1853,1877]" captionTargetBox="[159,1428,182,1825]" captionTargetId="figure-109@25.[151,1436,170,1830]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURES 86–94. Pseudomacroxiphus szentia details: 86–87, Titillators in ventro-distal view; 88, do. in latero-distal view; 89, do. in dorso-proximal view; 90–91, male abdominal apex in dorsal view; 92 female subgenital plate in ventral view; 93 do. in lateral view; 94, male stridulatory file on underside of left tegmen.—86–87, 91, 94, holotype male of P. szentia; 88–89, holotype male of P. atrifrons; 90, paratype male of P. atrifrons; 92–93, paratype female of P. atrifrons. Abbreviations: 10t tenth abdominal tergite; ce cercus; e epiproct; s stylus; sg subgenital plate. Scales = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5123664" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5123664/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 91</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,330,1556]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
Female. Tenth abdominal tergite furrowed in midline. Epiproct rounded, surface shallowly depressed. Cerci long, conical, slightly curved, apex acute. Ovipositor long, compressed, blade-shaped, substraight, highest at end of basal third (
<figureCitation box="[439,527,1170,1196]" captionStart="FIGURES 80–85" captionStartId="24.[151,269,1891,1915]" captionTargetBox="[244,1344,181,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-83@24.[236,1350,176,1867]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 80–85. Pseudomacroxiphus szentia: 80, male holotype of P. atrifrons; 81, female paratype of P. atrifrons; 82, frons holotype of P. atrifrons; 83, stridulatory area of left tegmen male holotype of P. szentia; 84, do. of right tegmen male paratype of P. atrifrons; 85, ovipositor female paratype of P. atrifrons. Scales = 1 mm (82–84) or 10 mm (81, 85)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5123660" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5123660/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 85</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,330,1556]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,338,1210,1236]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. Willemse" authorityYear="1961" box="[348,584,1211,1236]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Pseudomacroxiphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[348,584,1211,1236]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Pseudomacroxiphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the male pronotum not prolonged with the apex truncate and the paranota not deep. A character that it shares with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Karny" authorityYear="1912" box="[733,907,1251,1276]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Pseudonicsara" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[733,907,1251,1276]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Pseudonicsara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kirby" authorityYear="1906" box="[965,1059,1251,1276]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Habetia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[965,1059,1251,1276]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Habetia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It differs from both by the prolonged stridulatory area of the male tegmina and peculiar modifications of the phallic complex. From 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Karny" authorityYear="1912" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Pseudonicsara" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Pseudonicsara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it also differs by the fore tibia which is in cross-section quadrangular and by the long, compressed ovipositor. With 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kirby" authorityYear="1906" box="[346,440,1371,1396]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Habetia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[346,440,1371,1396]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Habetia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it also shares the rather flat, not conical meso- and metasternal lobes. It differs, apart from the above characters, by much longer wings, the possession of a baso-internal projection of the male cercus and the male phallic complex. The genus is not related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haan" authorityYear="1842" box="[894,1047,1451,1476]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Macroxiphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[894,1047,1451,1476]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Macroxiphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It differs by the morphology of pronotum and sternites, the modified stridulatory apparatus, male abdominal terminalia and titillators, female subgenital plate and even details of the ovipositor, although the latter is prolonged in both genera.
</paragraph>
